reviewText: Take me home was a movie that I only happened to find by chance -- it stars and is written/directed/produced by Parenthood star Sam Jaegar and this is just a fun ride.  They actually took a cab across country.  It's better than most romantic dramas and Sam Jaegar is just terrific.  Well written and a must see.
interesting plot that could of resulted in a deeper performance by the two leads with more interesting depth. All in all it is worth an hour and a half and as a result you will not regret it.

I don't wan't to spoil anythng by reveling the plot, but wanted to give my thoughts about this movie.  I saw  this movie while staying at a hotel. I truly enjoyed it. The actors had great chemistry & didn't overact the scenes. The movie moves smoothly (almost slow), but keeps you locked into the story. The scenery in the movie is beautiful.  I would love to see these actors together in another movie.
I really enjoyed this movie. It was very well acted and the storyline was interesting. There was a lot of depth to the characters.

"Just drive, that's what you said, just drive." Thom (Jaeger) is down on his luck. He can't get a job and just got kicked out of his apartment. In order to make money he decides to pretend he's a cab driver. After a few fares Claire (Jaeger) hails him down. She is also having a bad day and tells him to drive. So he does. I have gotten in the habit of not watching previews before watching a movie so I don't have any preconceived notions going in. I watched the preview for this one and really thought it would be a little boring. This was anything but boring. This movie takes two proved formulas and puts them together. A romantic comedy mixed with a road movie. The acting was OK and the budget for this was not the best but it was a great movie that is better then a lot of the high budget movies. This movie is pretty predictable but sometimes it works and this is an example of that. I tend to like the movies with an ending that isn't always happy but every once in a while a movie like this comes along and it just has a calming feeling when it works out the way it should. Overall, a very satisfying movie that deserves to be watched. I liked it a lot. I give it a B+.

A really enjoyable film with several scenes that might have you laughing out loud, even if you're watching the movie by yourself!

Sam and Amber Jaeger make a convincing couple and I had to wonder if a few of the scenes weren't ad libbed a bit, since they worked so well!

A great evening's entertainment which I would recommend for anyone over 13. I know we'll be watching "Take Me Home" again.
It moved well, funny but not mushy, unpredictable but believable. The end was worth the wait. A chic flick a guy would enjoy.

I loved it. I'm also very impressed that Sam wrote, directed, and stared in it. He's super talented. I thought it was really sweet that the main actors are married in real life. I suggest this to anyone that likes romantic comedy movies.

"Take Me Home" is a simple, charming, plausible story, well told.  It's not formulaic, smarmy, saccharine, or cute.  It's not rollicking, wild, or hysterical.  It's not tired, cliche-ridden, romantic rehash.  It is a fun, modestly-paced, clever, well-acted, carefully directed, clearly told, cleanly shot, elegant little comedy well worth watching.  I watched it twice, and found it consistently entertaining.

Look, I can suspend disbelief with the best of them, but throughout the movie you realize that these two disagreeable characters just HATE each other, and through the magic of physical proximity throughout the movie they wind up together at the end. He's essentially a con artist with an anger problem, while she just has the anger problem and a cheating husband. I watched the entire thing hoping for it to get better, and it just never did. Every funny line is in the trailer. I love indie movies and really wanted this to be watchable, since the husband and wife team wrote it and put it together and I understand how difficult it is to write and perform anythig. Want a charming indie? Go look up 2016's "Operator", and see the difference between quirky and flawed, but ultimately characters in that film vs. the generic paper-thin caricatures in this movie. I hate writing bad reviews, but I wish I'd never seen it. Two stars for getting off their butts and creating anything, but I sadly cannot recommend it.

After moving past the first 5-10 minutes of what felt like a bit overly-strained character development to set up the plot, the dialogue and scenarios begin to feel  possible, and you are able to escape into this all-too-human exploration into a question, "What is the foundation of a relationship?"  The symbolism of the cab--a rented relationship--is merely the beginning as this film delivers how relationships may transform, strengthen, or end.  A pleasant surprise!

I read the title and it seemed like something interesting I'd like to see. Driving from the East Coast to the West Coast is one of the most exhilarating experiences one can have in this great country. This movie didn't disappoint.

Thom, desperate for cash after being evicted from his apartment in New York City, is operating as an illegal taxi driver.  Claire, in an emotional crisis after catching her husband flirting with his assistant and learning that her estranged father has had a heart attack, hires him to drive her all the way to California.  The road trip leads to some humorous adventures, largely engendered by Thom's habitual lying and Claire's barely suppressed resentments.

This movie provided some interesting and light-hearted entertainment, but the ending ruined it! **Spoiler alert:  when Claire finally arrives in California, her husband is there waiting for her, full of apology for having turned to his assistant for friendship and support, but insisting that he "never crossed that line."  He assures Claire that he has broken off the relationship and wants to work on making their marriage better.  Yet in the end we see Claire throw it all away to pursue a relationship with Thom, who, although charming, has shown himself to be a self-serving liar and thief.  Don't get me wrong - I find Thom's character likeable in an appealing naughty-little-boy sort of way, but it's sad that once again Hollywood wants us to celebrate a woman ditching a man who is willing to put out the effort to build a good relationship in favor of the illusory 'freedom of the open road.'
This was a nice feel good movie with a couple of laughs.  I liked the characters and the story line, but I'm not sure it is something I would find myself recommending to someone else.

For me this movie was about the evolution of trust...  in the beginning there wasn't a lot of trust within each character.  The cabby wasn't being honest about his credentials, name, profession, etc...  he didn't trust people to accept him for him.  The cheating husband wasn't honest with the wife or with himself.  The wife didn't feel safe enough to be open about why she is traveling to CA... again a lack of trust.  As the movie progresses, each character begins to deal with their issues with trust at some level... some more successfully than others.  The wife of the cheater realizes that the cabby is not telling the whole truth, and yet must learn to trust him if they are to make it to CA.  The cabby comes to terms with his deceiving ways and in an amazing show of humility and respect, apologizes to her.  The cheating husband breaks off the affair, but fails to come to terms with the real issues in the relationship.  His journey with trust never quite gets him to where he really needs to go.  This film has a great deal of depth... and more than one journey is happening on the trip.

Scanning through the list of available films on Amazon, and not wanting to watch some high-tech, green screen crap, I caught the synopsis of "Take Me Home". Being a part-time Uber driver, it intrigued me (though I've never come close to this scenario). Very impressed with the character and story development, cinematography and sound track ... and the acting was very believable with an authentic development of the relationship between cabbie and cabbor (I know it's not a word, but you get it). As an Uber driver, someone getting in your car and saying, "just drive" probably isn't your best way to start a 'trip', especially if she YELLS at you to begin the ride. But in a movie, the suspension of disbelief works because you're anticipating something enjoyable to follow. This film does not disappoint.

A really cute movie about real life struggles.  Made me laugh, cry and feel hope.  Hope that there is someone out there for me and that someday I may just run into him when I least expect it... Great clean movie.

This is clearly a movie made from the heart. It's a family affair, with many Jaegers in it - the two starring roles but also the side parts. A charming story that works because the rapport and dialogue between the two main characters are excellent.

I did not care for this movie at all.  Although the two main actors did not have a lot to work with in this script, neither of them captured my imagination, affection, respect, or even interest.  I stuck with it to the bitter end thinking that it would get better or that somehow these two characters would come alive.  The woman Claire is self-absorbed, selfish, cold, and a very good definition of "a bitch".  She shows no warmth, feeling, concern (much less love) for anybody throughout the movie. Except for a couple of long stares near the end, she shows no feeling or attachment to the man (Thom).  He is at least a bit likable, although its frustrating to see him stumble from one self imposed disaster to another.  He is patient, far more than I can imagine any man being with such a selfish, bratty woman.  Clearly, he needs approval, respect, and love in his lonely, failing life.  Hard to imagine that he thinks he can get it from this woman.  Therefore, the ending is simply ridiculous.  The movie did not at all develop a blossoming relationship between the two based on anything other that their mutual need to get out of the several messes they get themselves into. Don't waste your time.  It is not the impulsive adventure, with excitement and some fun, that pulls these two together romantically as we are led to believe by the storyline description. The dour, whiney music score adds to the drag that this movie becomes from the very beginning and sustains for 90 minutes. simply a total waste of time.

This film is a beautiful look at two people trying to make sense of their lives. As they meet and get to know each other, the intensity builds, both between the two of them, and in the film as whole. By the end, you are completely drawn in to the story, and waiting to see how things will turn out. Highly recommended.

The dialogue was flat and uninspired, they used a few 'trick shots' with the camera to set up a shot that never carries through. It starts off with the introduction to the main characters but never fully finishes that part before awkwardly putting them together. A good try and I give them credit for that, but the road trip premise is a tired one.

The beginning is slow to start, but once she's in the cab and he's driving -- it flows really effortless and authentically. To me it was not cheesy, and the relationship unraveled in a natural, yet interesting pace. The characters are multifaceted and really make the movie better than the mediocre storyline. I liked the fact that they did not SPOILER! **kiss at the end* It made the connection of two people seem more intimate and vulnerable. Even the smaller characters charms made the film stand apart. So pleasantly surprised and would definitely recommend it.

Loved this film! It went from zero to 40 with the first 10 minutes, then hits about 65-70 MPH for most of the movie. It's a road trip with a lot of differences.  This is a far more realistic husband and wife (real life) film than most others we can see with actors sharing parts of their first names. It is alternately sad, confusing, funny, chaotic, thoughtful, with a few repeats, and definitely intriguing as we are along for the ride.

What I liked best is how the film unwinds with stops along the NYC to San Diego journey at about the same speed as information is revealed about Dan and Claire. They are less able to reveal the truths about themselves than most strangers on a bus between San Antonio and Austin. Yet, as they do, there are surprises, sweet and bittersweet.

I am so used to Superheroes (primarily Marvel), Star Trek, or Star Wars dragging me into the action at light speed (give or take a warp) that begins quickly and does not quit until after the credits when someone looks out at the audience and tells us to go home.

This film is not what usually happens, yet if your stay with it until she orders the cabbie to "JUST DRIVE!!" and he does so, everything begins to have a steadier beat - or not - yet it is really interesting. This film seven audience awards as film festivals from Boston across the country to the Napa Valley.

It you are an adult who would like time-out from time in the 23rd Century, or a galaxy far far away, or having to listen to Thor bragging about how much better he is than Cap, this would be a great alternative.

SPOILER WARNING: In a nutshell, non-profit married NY lady finds husband in a suspicious meeting with coworker in their home.  She also finds out her dad, with whom she's had very little contact over the years, is dying.  She leaves NY in a cab to go see her dad in CA without telling her husband.  Understandably she's distraught.  She and said cab, who has a big suitcase of his own issues he's lugging along, begin to get used to one another.  In the end, they reach CA in time to attend her father's funeral, where her husband is waiting on her.  He confesses that he had been discussion their relationship issues with his coworker and had too many personal conversations but that it never went beyond too-personal conversations.  He admits it shouldn't have happened and that he was breaking things off with said coworker, and that he was willing to do whatever it took to work on their marriage.  In the end, she moves out and eventually tracks down cab driver to presumably start a relationship with him.  I am opposed to the message here that when you don't feel love toward someone it's then okay to walk away from a marriage.  Or that a marriage is not worth working diligently to preserve (not including situations of abuse or affairs).  NY lady apparently had a personal epiphany that she wasn't happy any longer and wanted out of her marriage so that was that...
something different!  Good

I can't tell if this is an indie film that lacked the courage of its convictions and flinched at the end to win eyeballs, or a traditional rom com with an inadvertently subversive subtext. Ultimately it disappoints by trying to have it both ways, and in the end neither of the characters, so appealing through most of the film, are all that attractive... but then, are any of us? So again, is this actually a good movie? If only I knew what the writer/director intended... whether he knew what he doing or whether this incongruity is an accident. I am not normally put off by ambiguity, but I guess I wanted either an indie film that along its quirky path exposed the hazards in our efforts to relate to another person thanks to our imperfections, or a traditional rom com that won out by being the cream that rises above the limitations of the genre as the good ones do. But this dogs breakfast... I can neither cheer the triumph of love nor mourn the heartache of its loss. And I find myself indifferent to what happens to these two people next.

I'd seen this film before & wanted to watch just the opening again last night before going to bed. I ended up watching the whole thing a second time around - staying up way later than I had planned. What an enjoyable movie! Solid script writing & fine acting. Good old fashions  story telling with some modern twists. A love story that doesn't overdo it, doesn't beat you over the head about love. It just lays that part of the story out for you to enjoy & even laugh a little.

However, just like any Hollywood movies, it falls into the cliche of climaxing at the oversimplified version of happily together forever. Transcendental romance is the only thing being played again and again nowadays. And it's important to see the value of it being not constantly exaggerated.

As this movie began, I wondered if it would be simply another badly written, low-budget movie whose plot I would quickly lose interest in.  As the movie played on, I found myself caught up in the story.  Eventually, I also realized the acting was really good.  When I can watch a movie without being distracted by the acting, I consider the actors to be very good.  Nothing was overacted.  The characters were completely believable.  In the end, the story was also pretty emotional and well-written.  How cute to discover that the main actors are real-life husband and wife!  I hope they find the time and money to create some more works of this kind.  Apparently, it doesn't take a huge budget and big name actors to make a completely engrossing movie.  Fun find.

I enjoyed the movie while I watched it, and I enjoyed the ending immensely, but I was left afterward feeling that the jump between the characters' relationship at the beginning of the movie to the end of the movie didn't develop smoothly enough.  In other words, I didn't see a logical progression throughout the movie from indifferent (or at times, in a classicly New York way, antagonistic) to liking each other to potentially loving each other.  The scenes that were designed to be critical points where the character's feelings "came around" or deepened didn't adequately convey that.  The acting is fine, and the writing is okay, but I think it was the writing that really held the movie back.  Just a little more refinement at a few critical points in the movie could've made this a rom-com classic - and for that, it gets four stars and is worth a watch if you're scrolling for something you haven't seen before and nothing jumps out at you.

After I warmed up to Amber Jaeger's character,Claire, I really enjoyed the movie.  She seemed too"bitchy", don't know if I can use that word here but that best describes the character,  Thom played by Sam Jaeger,  is that guy you just want to pull for because it seems his world would be a nice place if he just had a chance.  Woman of ice Claire, learns to trust and love again after realizing her perfect world was not perfect and neither are human beings.  The scene where they arrive at the home of Thom's, parents, Lynette and Arnold, is one of the best in the film and a lot of  great acting takes place right there.  Michelle Krusiec as Suzanne is that cute innocent likable girl who is funny as she shares her romance stories of the latest guy with her boss.  The movie ends just like you hoped it you would so you might find yourself still smiling and staring at the credits.

I looked past this movie probably a hundred times while searching for a good romance to watch. I finally watched it after reading the reviews. I'm not sure if I was judging it based on the cover or the title or what, who knows, but I'm glad I finally watched it. This movie is beautifully written, acted, and directed! From the obvious chemistry between the two leads to the down to earth dialogue, this movie was fantastic. I don't want to spoil anything, but don't judge this movie based on the cover like I did. I just finished it and it's my new favorite romance. It's refreshing to watch a movie that's well made, where the characters aren't bringing each other down, and the scenery is stunning. This movie made me want to drive cross country! Love, love, love it! If you enjoy a good romance, or even just a good movie, then sit down and watch this one!

This movie looked predictable, and maybe a tad bit boring.  That I gave it a try in the first place can be blamed on having too much time on my hands, and nothing to lose as it is free to stream for Prime members.  But this one stepped beyond the usual boundaries of the "road trip film" formula, without ever quite breaking through the realism barrier -- a fine line to walk.  It had some truly laugh-out-loud moments for me, and some beautiful settings, but the real redeeming qualities all lay with the acting.  Each character was so well done, that this alone breathed life into what would otherwise have been a mediocre script.  I found the ending to be a little bit less conclusive than I would have liked, but the pacing was decent, and it did have an over-all feeling of completion, and the scenes mostly flowed well together.  Not a show stopper, but better than 50% of what they regularly show in theaters, so if you are looking for something sweet and sentimental, you may enjoy this.

I don't write reviews that often, but I simply had to write something about this film. I stumbled onto it looking for something heartwarming, funny, a run-of-the-mill romantic comedy. Initially, I figured it was just gonna be exactly what I thought, but it snuck up on me, and before I realized it, the end was near and I was totally engrossed! I'm not really familiar with either of the actors or their work, so I was quite pleasantly surprised at the great job the actors did. What really got to me was the simple reality of both of the characters and their lives. I could see myself in the woman. I could also see my daughter in her. This wonderfully eclectic piece of work really caught me off guard. I was hooked from the moment that Claire told Dan/Thom to "just drive!" It was a double surprise to find out the two main characters are married in real life! They played their parts so beautifully! And the chemistry! How it built up gradually from the initial annoyances was just darling! Pretty much no foul language, no sex scenes, no violence... what's a girl to think? That there ARE good movies out there without all that stuff! Who knew?  I also loved the soundtrack and the scenery... fit perfectly! This film may not be for everyone, but it was definitely for me! Loved it!

This was a flat, unimaginative movie. All throughout, that was all the lady did, was to throw temper tantrums whenever something didn't go her way. And she never talked about any of her problems - she just physically threw things. That basically was her whole personality, and the focus of the whole movie; watching an adult spoiled brat.

And the guy that drove her cross country just put up with anything she dished out, which was too unreal too. Nobody in their right mind would put up with that.

In a way, I even felt that the movie is an insult to women, and men too. The only thing the lady has going for her is that she's very pretty. Therefore, she can act however she wants, and the guy puts up with anything she dishes out?

And, then she goes off from her corporate world to... live with him? I don't think so.

I would like to give this movie a better rating than 3 stars, but watching her throw things every time something went wrong (which were her own faults) wasn't very captivating. I kept watching it, thinking that surely something else would happen, but the only thing that changed was perhaps the objects that she threw or punched or broke, or whatever.

There are better movies to choose from.

What a fun picture with a couple that seemingly is so different but finally sees their shared qualities and disappointments.  Amber Jaeger is sharp and acerbic, her eyes darting this way and that as if nobody is ever going to pull a fast one on her, especially not her husband.  So when she grows a bit disenchanted, imagine her running into a goofy doofus of a cabdriver who seems to be a nice guy that's broke and wanting to take advantage of her despair (and her money).  But things take a turn and they find that before long, the tables have turned.  Not one to give up, either of them, the heels dig in and soon you're on one rowdy ride across the country...in a cab!  It's a fun trip, and the brother-sister team seem to have fun portraying this couple (discovered at the end, or so it seems with their same last names), their fights almost exactly what you would picture and far from the Hollywood norm.  Worth watching if you're feeling down...this is a Hallmark movie for adults.

At first I felt this movie was a letdown after watching first 30 minutes as I hadn't read much of the description and thought it was going to be a funny movie, not a dramatic movie with subtle humor. So I skipped to the end as I was intially bored. However watching the end made me curious and I wanted to give the movie a proper chance. It seemed evident that this movie was more than meets the eye. And it is. It is a drama for sure however with strong performances from the lead actor and actresses. It was character and image driven more than dialogue. By image i mean there are some beautiful imagery/videography scenes that capture the emotions of the characters and the scenes of classic open fields. I appreciated that there was no cursing, college (ie unimaginative) humor, and not even a kiss. The movie is about the changes that occur within both Claire and Thom. Also gave a side lesson on the consequences of habitually lying and the power of understanding/forgiving/trusting. Finally, the soundtrack fits the movie very nicely and in fact, I'm keen on buying a couple of the tracks.  A very good movie that impressed me.

Two strangers are thrown together on a long taxi-ride across America. Although this movie is earnest and sincere, and worthy of your viewing consideration, it is a bit formulaic and predictable. The basic plot is this [no spoilers]: a NYC businesswoman surprises her husband in an apparently compromising situation with another woman, so she hails a Yellow Cab and decides--more or less on a whim--to have the cabbie  drive her to California to see her father who is recovering from a heart attack. Along the way the cabbie and his passenger confront their lives, learn about each other, and reveal their shortcomings. This 90-minute low-budget movie's ambition exceeds its grasp. I'd give it 3 and 1/2 stars if I could--somewhere between "Okay" and "Like".

One of the most underrated movies ever! It's touching, funny, whimsical, delightful, and absolutely captivating. Honestly, a great movie. Most of the reviewers that rated it one star didn't give it a chance. They just gave up between the five and ten minute mark, and you can't really judge a movie you watched for five minutes. It's not really a fast paced movie with tons of jokes and what passes for witty dialog. It's smart, and the plot really draws you in. It's beautifully shot, and even though the premise was a bit absurd it worked somehow. It isn't overly pretentious and esoteric; it's straightforward. It's much more worthwhile than half the s***ty movies I'm usually stuck watching, due to a sad lack of wifi and the fact that I had the DVD laying around for ten years, some of which even being stoned out of your mind can't help (looking at you, American Pie Beta House).

I really hesitated watching a movie made by Africaaners (white South Africans). As I feared, the racism of a post apartheid society is so ingrained in Africaaners still. It exposes the prejudices of a people that still want their experiences to be deemed as more valid this side of apartheid. The colonialist condescension is too much to stomach, not to mention laughably silly for its desperate grasping to inflate their collective racist egos. 2 early scenes in particular demonstrate this. 1st scene: when the white family had adopted a black African child and the family remarks that he takes it so seriously as if it was an additional and special honor to be adopted by a white family. 2nd scene: where the black African gas attendant clutches his heart melodramatically for the protagonists... as if the banal dramas of countless customers elicits such response on any self respecting customer service professional. Condescending racist trope much? I'm sure more such gems will follow.

This is a cute and well acted film. Claire is overwhelmed with circumstances out of her control. This is her journey, physically and emotionally, back to the things in life that matter most. Thom escorts her on this road trip of discovery and along the way we see how much he has truly hidden from himself and his own family.  The story reveals their failures without dwelling on them or making one's life struggles greater than another's. The humor is well placed throughout. I really admire that the language chosen throughout was clean. I don't remember a curse word. There were adult themes but no bedroom or overt displays of affection. Kudos!

A very good movie, even better if you get to watch it for Free on Amazon Prime.  Another reviewer said that these two have great chemistry ... turns out they are married in real life.  They made a great movie together.  He is a down-on-his-luck cab driver, although he's really not a cab driver ... he just pretends to be in his cab bought at auction.  It helps him make fast cash in the big city of NY and he needs cash as he's just been evicted from his rental apartment and his career can't get off the ground.  She's having an early mid-life crisis and offers to pay him $5000 to take her to California where her father is seriously ill.  A father she hasn't seen in maybe 20 years.  The trip gets complicated and these two don't know if they hate each other, trust each other, or can finish the trip together.  It's not one smooth ride from the east coast to the west coast but in 5 days they may get to know each other a little more but they still don't know if they hate each other, trust each other, or can even finish the trip together.  They each learn something about themselves.  He learns about himself.  She learns about herself. Both came from expectations upon them and hurts that resulted in them not feeling good enough. Surprisingly fresh and well done.  The story involves a woman (Claire) running from a marriage in which she discovers her husband is possibly having an affair and a man (Thom) who is completely down and out who happens to own a former taxicab.  She mistakes him for a real cabbie and he is willing to drive her wherever she wants to go for a fare -- which happens to be to California to see her ailing and estranged father.  The story is a road trip and the evolving relationship between the two propels the story along.  We gradually learn about their respective pasts just as they learn about each other.

The theme of the movie is truth-telling.  The central line in the movie is Thom's, after he makes a full confession to Claire of all his errors, omissions, and lies.  He says, "And I will never lie to you again."  To which she replies, "I know."  And that is the hinge-point of the story.

This movie is rated PG-13, I suppose for some foul language.  There isn't anything objectionable in this movie other than that.  No sex scenes, even implied.  The developing relationship between the two is completely platonic.  If I have any objection to the movie it is that (spoiler alert) after attempting to rebuild her marriage with her husband, it doesn't work out for Claire and she seeks out Thom in the final scene.  But this is a nice, fun ride (pun intended).  Husband and wife actors Sam and Amber Jagger are very good together.  Their chemistry and witty repartee are a lot of fun.  A thumbs up from me.

Driving across the country is a theme, no a recipe, for finding your lost way.  There have been many similar journeys in movies and in literature.  I like reading about them and comparing them. This is one of most enjoyable romantic comedies I've come across in a long time. The chemistry between the leading actors is fabulous, and the plot is unique and filled with surprises. The scenery is beautiful as well. Both women and men will enjoy this delightful romantic movie, especially since it lacks the soppiness that might turn some guys off. Hope you have the chance to see it. Enjoy!

Sam Jaeger writes, directs and stars in this romantic and believable situation comedy. This is neither overblown nor timid while costarring his own wife in the opposite lead role.  Scenery mixes with a definite palpable chemistry as these two take to the road for a trip that does not start with the happiest of farewells.

Thom (Sam Jaeger) is struggling to pay his rent. He's falling behind so he has to make money quickly.  He decides to drive a cab while living in New York City, although without proper licensing to drive it and carrying many of his possessions in his back seat.  Not having another choice, he picks up a hopeful but desperate fare in Claire.

Claire (Amber Jaeger), who is a high-powered businesswoman, catches her husband at their home in an obviously questionable situation with another woman. This woman compliments her on the "color of her bedroom" before leaving their home.  Within the same time frame, she receives a call to let her know that her father has had a heart attack and is hospitalized. These things happen just at the same time it all hits the fan with her marriage.  This causes her to run out into the street and randomly grab a cab that just so happens to be Thom.  In a "Shut up and just drive" situation, it is a go and Go Now!  The eventual destination is Encinitas, CA, but as far as Claire is concerned, anywhere would be better than where she is at the moment.

This is an easier, sometimes sarcastic, mix of a story, being more subtle than in your face as it gains momentum.  The action is slower paced and the humor comes at you at the same speed though there are some definite laughs catching one right out loud.  The couple goes from one mishap to another in some gorgeous and well shown scenery (Jesse Feldman), from the Big City to Middle America, and onward.  This is all scored with some original and snappy music by 'Bootstraps' all coming together very well for an enjoyable movie that I would absolutely watch again.

The movie was funny and smart. The plot was original - maybe not an epic but it was inspired and different than the cookie cutter romantic comedies that are being spat out onto the screen these days. It was a refreshing watch.

Quick Overview: Claire receives the news her father has a heart attack and, hysterical, she hails a cab and tells the driver, "Drive." Thom, perhaps confused and maybe intrigued, complies. To his surprise, he winds up driving all the way from New York to California. On the long road trip they build a fast friendship and then some.

"Take Me Home" is a clean and innocent romantic comedy. I only noticed a couple stray curses. Other than that it is pretty family friendly.

Amber Jaeger plays Claire, who is charged emotionally and somewhat stubborn. Thom, who is played by her real-life husband, Same Jaeger, seems like he is still trying to figure a few things out. He may have had a hard go at life too. Both are fun to watch and easy to like. Their banter is laughable and their connection, while not really passionate, is still obvious.

The very end is formulaic and unimaginative, but that is forgiven with the strength of the film otherwise and how endearing the characters are, and how happy you are that they *spoiler* get together.

I was bothered by one small scene in the beginning but the main character addresses it and apologizes for it later so I appreciated that. The leads have great chemistry which is probably partially due to them being married in real life, but (let's be honesty) at the same time we've all seen married couples have poor chemistry on screen too and so I think we can safely say their excellent acting played a big role too. I like road trip films/books/tropes and this one wasn't as predictable as I thought it was going to be. Sure there are a few expected tropes, but they were well done. This one was good enough for me to buy it to keep. It's one I can see lounging around and putting on during a lazy weekend. Highly recommended.
This was simply a wonderful journey to experience. Beautifully done, wonderful story. I especially loved the end! :))))) Heart warming. I thank goodness for wonderful movies like this.

What a great movie and a surprise to find it...easy, honest, and original.  The music is also enjoyable and really complimented the movie.

Though this movie is listed as a 'Romantic Comedy', it's not over the top Hollywood romance or comedy.  It's a solid story about two individuals who have struggles personally and professionally.  Through their trip together they become aware of these life faults and somehow each manages to overcome.  The story is mixed with subtle humor, chemistry, great supporting quirky characters, great acting by the lead roles wrapped with original music from a band who formed together for this movie.

Finally, the ending is one of the best I've seen in a long time since two strangers become friends and now the imagination leads to their new romance which may start 'guilt free'.

Hope Sam and Amber Jaeger do another movie together and great to find out that they are married husband and wife in real life.  When I saw the credits at the end of the movie, I was surprised to see the last names to be the same and also other characters with same last name.  I would guess more relationships/friends who supported this low budget and very entertaining movie.

I don't normally endorse but the movie, music, low budget, and story behind it all really captured me.  I hope you will share with others and Enjoy!

The 2 actors have such great chemistry, no wonder they're married in real life.

Great movie. Slow start but great overall

A husband and wife project that was done really well. It was a very interesting plot and I think most people could identify with some part of the movie. Overall well worth checking out, I watched it twice!!!
A sleeper of a movie, but the characters are very likable and the film was enjoyable and uplifting.  I recommend.
I'm a Sam Jaeger fan from Parenthood so I watched it.  I wasn't disappointed. Good chemistry between the two actors which is handy because they're married off screen.
If you watch the movie backwards, it's about a woman who leaves a man (who's progressively leaves the friend zone) & travels great lengths so that she can be with her faithful husband.

I am always amazed when I find a gem on Netflix.  This was a real diamond!
Funny, sad, romantic... all the reasons we go to the movies.
Sorry it didn't get seen by a lot more people.
It beats the "big" name romantic films out in the theaters, no contest.
Saw this movie in 2011 at the end of the Nashville film festival and left cheered, and cheering, at the utter magic of this film.  The soundtrack adds to it, as well.

I saw Sam Jaeger on @Parenthood and just think he is such a good actor and portrays (very well) the husband and father all women would like to have.  When I Googled him and saw this movie starred he and his real-life wife, I couldn't resist.  It did not disappoint; I am a fan of them both now.  Thank you!
One of my favorite movies. Watch it over and over. Originally saw it on Netflix but wanted to have a permanent copy.
A good story with a lot of loop holes in it but it will keep your attention for the entire movie.
So I'm reviewing this months after viewing it and honestly can't remember the plot.  I only recall the feeling it left me with -- satisfied to have seen something different enough to be refreshing.

I like movies that aren't something I've seen before. This fits that bill. However, I had trouble relating to either character who both seemed to have problems handling what appear to be pretty straight forward life choices.
This movie was very good.  And the music in it was very good as well.  I enjoyed it very much.
This movie wasn't very funny. In fact the funniest and best parts were watching the trailer. I wouldn't rent it.

This movie was sweet and funny.  The two main characters were very good actors and so good together, and it was a pleasant surprise to find out they are husband and wife in real life.  I laughed out loud and even cried some.  I didn't expect to enjoy this movie so much, but I did.
Interesting premise if one felt it could actually happen but it didn't "suspend disbelief" for me as a story should. Some moments....some unnecessary scenes....watch it on sale night.

Like Jason, we gave this one 45 minutes then couldn't take it any more.  The plot is full of holes and the lame dialogue isn't helped by terrible acting.  I would much rather sit alone in a room with the lights out than have to watch one more second of this fourth rate mess.  Leonard Pinth Garnell would have loved this one--"Dreadful!!  Simply awful!!"

This is a wonderful movie that even some die hard chick flick hating men will enjoy. Wonderful acting, great characters and a heart felt story that delivers first frame to last. Never overacted but done with beautiful pacing and editing that leads you through the story scene by scene. I never knew what would happen next but I hoped and was not disappointed. Sam and Amber really did it right with this great little film. Watch it alone or with someone you love. 5 stars.

I recently watched "Take Me Home," and just really loved it. The actors are wonderful and talented, and there was never a dull moment in the film. I highly recommend this film as it is clever and original. Enjoy!

My husband and I rented this on a whim and we loved it! I am a Sam Jaeger fan (Parenthood, Eli Stone) and was surprised to find out that he also wrote and directed this film. Good story line but the acting made it great. Very thought-provoking. I will watch it again.
Take Me Home was a surprise. I thought it would be okay, and I love romantic comedies. This was much more humorous and interesting than I expected, and I would watch it again.

What a great find and pleasant surprise this movie was for me. I found it to be intelligent yet whimsical, painful yet funny, and most of all, thoroughly entertaining. As I watched this movie, it became very apparent to me that it was truly a labor of love by those most involved in making it -- producers, writer, director, actors,etc. It also is a beautifully filmed movie that reminded me that we are blessed to live in a magnificent and diverse country. I will recommend this movie to friends and continue to look for other independent film projects involving the Jaegers in the future.

I didn't like the movie at first...it seemed aimed at a  20-something audience.  The soundtrack underlined that impression.  Another road trip, I thought, with two characters with warring personalities  who will encounter troubles and eventually fall in love.  A tried and true formula.

But somehow I stuck with it, probably because the actors were very good.  I really liked the angry young woman and then the shluppy cab driver warmed up to me.  There were some good stops along the way.  The guy's family in Boulder was perfect. I loved his uptight dad and his mom who kept saying "How Fun!"  Then, the girl's sweet eccentric mom in Las Vegas....a heartwarmer.  The scene at the memorial service was a little maudlin for me and the only scene that didn't ring true. The end was trite, too, but somehow, by that time I had forgiven them all.

After I saw the film I learned that the lead actor, Sam Jaeger,also wrote and directed the film and his leading woman is his real-life wife, Amber.  It makes sense, as they had such perfect chemistry and the whole film had that warmth about it that comes from a labor of love. I'd like to seem them together again, maybe in something with a little more depth.

PS.  A week later.  I just saw another "romantic road trip" film that I think is worthy of comparison to this one.  It's a French film, "As the Sea Rises" and in my opinion, is a much better film...much less formulaic and predictable...It has characters who don't look like movie stars and their lives are much more interesting and realistic.  I recommend it.
Nice to enjoy a movie that takes you away and leaves you with a good feeling!  Good love story. Wonderful actors. It was a delightful quirky love story.  I would definitely recommend.

This movie was great, not what I expected and that is what makes it work so well. I had to stop several times to do chores, and I coulden't stop thinking what was next! Now I'm trying to buy the sound track.
Nice story. Easy to watch and has nice sceneryplot. Actors were good and easy to listen to and understand. Plot was easy to follow.

I liked this movie. I really was just renting it to see what it was about, and I ended up liking it more than I figured. The likehood of someone getting in a cab and driving that far is definately not going to happen, but itwas funny the adventures they had along the way. It is a good movie to watch on the couch with dinner and enjoy

I had never heard of this movie before choosing to watch it a few nights ago. Both my husband and I thoroughly enjoyed it and thought it was a touching and compelling story. At the end of the film we found out that the stars were husband and wife  which made it even more special. If you're tired of  the shoot'em up, blown 'em up with crazy special effects movie and if you're looking for a smart, interesting plot driven story choose this one!

Despite the appearance of accolades and novelty, this film is insufferably boring from start to finish. Character development is tepid; humor is forced; plot is weak. Although many of the reviews I read on this film prior to purchasing were (perhaps overly) positive, in this instance I was totally misled. Considering the amount of positive feedback, I suspect that there are many fans of small budget indie films who will enjoy this movie. Sadly, I am not one of them and I would caution anyone thinking about renting this film: try renting from your local library.

This was written, and directed by the male lead character.  The romantic female lead is his wife, and it kind of feels like it.  I kept thinking it was a great story but it could have really been better directed.  The premise is good (I won't go through that here, you've probably already read it in the description if you are interested to read people's reviews), the acting is good, and--for a lower budget film--the production is quite good. It just seems to fall flat in areas you would expect to fall on the shoulders of the director. For example some scenes tend to slow the momentum and other scenes might as well have been shortened, or deleted altogether.  Overall it wasn't a bad movie at all.  I liked it, and thought it was better than a "just okay" three-star rating.  If you like romantic comedy/dramas you probably won't be disappointed.  They aren't my favorite. However, my wife--a big fan--did liked it.

This was an unexpected surprise and Sam did a great job writing, producing, and directing it. (as well as acting)  I didn't realize that was his real life wife, and enjoyed her acting a great deal.  Very nicely done.

This is a classic comedy situation:  two people with clashing personalities get stuck together on a cross-country journey with a variety of delays and setbacks.  Why is this one so good?

The plot is not particularly original, and the scenes are not incredibly original, creative or surprising. There are some holes in the plot--but they can be ignored well enough. However, the acting is fantastic and the characters are appealing--both the lead actors have great comedic timing. The little surprises in plot and dialogue are cute and funny. The characters are realistic and you like them both equally. The filming, editing, and music are done very well.

We found ourselves chuckling out loud quite a bit during the movie, and when it ended, it left us feeling good and happy. We were quite surprised to see one of the scenes shot in a parking lot near our small town in SE Ohio. Small world! But we got a kick out of that!
It was the best movie that we've seen in a long time. Highly recommend it as a romantic comedy with substance. I'm looking forward to this actor/director's next movie.

I can not express how thought-provoking this movie was, and it was done in such an artistic, delightful way.  Each scene, though seemingly unimportant on the surface, was artfully crafted, taking on greater meaning and speaking volumes as the movie travels onward.  Though the characters(who are opposites) appear to be running away from their lives, are really reconnecting with them: their pasts and their futures.  All at the same time. Together.  It was amazing.  This movie is HUGE.  I haven't seen anything like it in a very long time.  It's the kind of movie you can't stop thinking about after viewing it.  So, do not turn it off or you'll deprive yourselves of seeing each layer, more emotionally raw than the last one, peeled away.  And you'll realize that no one, on the surface, is really what they seem.  However, you'll feel satisfied by the end of it, because you'll know that each character will heal.  It is a truly amazing story to watch.  The acting was perfect!  Thank you to those who put their hearts and souls into it!  We marveled at it and enjoyed it immensely!  We will be watching it again and recommending it to all our friends!
Bad acting, story and shooting. Don't waste your money or your time. God I hope Amazon builds up a more decent collection of videos soon.

Well worth the rental. I can see why it achieved so many award/nominations. Whenever I see films with many of those, I give them a try and this one, as many others, did not let me down.  Funny, moving, and hopeful.  Sure, it's a movie cliche, but wouldn't it be great if everyone found what they found, without all the hustle, bustle, and material things in the world that many choose to see instead of the person within?  I think so.
Rented this on a whim.  Highly recommended!  Two people whose lives are fraying around them end up taking a cross country road trip that is funny, sweet, and transformative for each of them.
My wife and I watched this recently and thoroughly enjoyed it. Not a complicated movie and a little predictable but definitely worth watching. Loved the Jaegers!

I was pleasantly surprised by this movie.  When you read the description, you think, "Ok, that will be fair."  But there were SEVERAL plot turns that caught me completely off guard, and that is something that doesn't happen with today's movies.  Very enjoyable.  it's not an "action" flick, so at times it seems a bit slow...but that's when they throw you with something unexpected.
This is the best movie I have seen in a long time.  Acting, music, scenery, and story line was superb!  I would highly recommend this movie to anyone!

This is an incredible movie with a good plot, great acting, and realistic, well-written dialog.  This film does not remind me of anything I've ever watched before, which makes it all that much more interesting.  Although most women will love this movie, it is definitely not a chick-flick and guys will like it just as much.  As others have written, there are no special effects, no car chases, and no big name stars.  What is does have is a good story and some wonderful acting.  The scenery is realistic because the movie was actually filmed on a road trip across the country.  The two main stars (Sam and Amber Jaeger) are married in real life and Sam directed this gem.  The heart of this movie is the interaction between the two as they face personal issues and physical hurdles together and learn more about each other as well as about themselves.  Sit back and enjoy the ride.
I don't want to say too much. This movie is worth-watching if you enjoy independent movies. I will watch again. Incredibly honest movie. Loved it!
This is a very enjoyable movie. Great characters, plot, music, photography. The ultimate outcome might be a little predictable, but still well done with a satisfying ending.
The movie lacked everything: plot, acting, drama, humor! Please don't waste your time watching it; it was a drag. I had to force myself to finish the movie...

I kept waiting for it to get better. It didn't. The actors had chemistry, but it never amounted to anything. The characters were all a bit shameful as well. There was not one character you could really root for. Ugh. Waste of time.
Had my attention from beginning to end. Great acting, good story, interesting characters. This movie deserves a wider audience.  It's very good.

It was so nice to see a movie with acting not just special effects. Great acting, great story, great directing. This is a clean good movie that you can feel comfortable referring to a friend. It is amazing that hollywood can't figure out how to make good movies like this anymore. I can't say enough good about the movie. I wish this could have been a box office hit, it deserved so much more. If it only had the distribution, PR and hype that other movies get I am sure it would have done well.

This is the best movie I've seen in a long time. If you are tired of the cookie cutter remakes, try this movie for a refreshing breath of fresh air!

Everything great, but I want to buy the sound track.  Is there one?  The story kept me guessing as the who really Dan Reeves really was.
gerald
Very enjoyable movie. well worth watching. Not to mushy for a guy to watch with you. Loved the guys attitude. More like a real guy would act.
I just keep thinking this movie was going become real good but NO. no no no no no no no hell no!
I love great little movies like this that completely take you by surprise. Music is wonderful and actors bring a solid performance.

This was a good movie which I liked because it was refreshing.  I call it refreshing because it was not overdone, ridiculous, or cheesy.  It just seemed like a good movie where those involved thought about it and cared about it.  It was refreshing to watch a normal movie that was created on purpose.  Not all time, but solid.

WOW.  This film is one of the best films I've seen ever and the best film seen this year.  This film will connect with so many people on many different levels.  It is a great movie from the standpoint of romantic comedy or independent or drama or comedy:  It fits all of those genres and more.  Excellent writing and the characters are spot-on and you will find yourself reminiscing about your own relationships not only with your partner, but also with your family members.  The music is absolutely amazing, especially the music by Bootstraps (Fortyfive) and all I can say is this is a movie that I bought to keep forever because it is that wonderful.  Watch it and you will see that it will change your heart forever.  Congratulations to you, Sam Jaeger, for outstanding writing, directing, and acting and to Amber Jaeger for your sensitive and intuitive acting. To both of you, I will be looking forward to your next work. To anyone considering film work as an art, this movie will inspire you.  WONDERFUL, AMAZING, INSPIRING, MOVING FILM...THANK YOU.
It just goes to show that one does not need "mega stars" to make a very good movie. Very romantic. Well done.

...I already love this movie.
It all feels so seamless from the opening scene, to the dialogue, the framing and cinematography of the shots, and on to the music. To top it off, the acting has a naturalism to it that it's real enough to make me slightly ashamed for peeping. I am pleased.
Great acting! Sam is multi talented!
relaxed and enjoyable watch
Movie was good, but I don't like how it ended.

loved loved loved loved it a lot.
This is what i call it a movie! <3

Look, I'd like to rate this movie higher and perhaps if the "writers" allowed someone else to play the lead roles, I might have watched it to the end.
But it's basically the exact same storyline of Ed Burns and his first 'love interest", Maxine Bahns, and the first 25 minutes of "She's the One".
I really wish people in Hollywood would learn, there's NEVER any on-screen chemistry with spouses.
What's worse, just like the aforementioned and even Branjolina ( see it didn't even spell correct that ridiculous name ) never deliver the building torch that the audience needs, to believe.

Please stop, trying to be cool and star in an "indy" movie with your spouse.
For Ch$%&t sake, if Stanley Kubrick couldn't make it feasible for Nicole and Tom ( small, barf ),
I think we can call it...  No?  How about a definite - NO.
Pretty good way to waste time.

I absolutely loved this movie!  The developing relationship between Thom and Claire (real life husband and wife) is just so moving and so real.  The movie was at times funny, at times sad, and at times just plain insane.  But it worked.  This is the best movie I have ever seen that nobody has ever heard of.  It does not even have a rating on Rotten Tomatoes because I guess there are too few reviews.  But you know what?  I am now going to buy "Take Me Home" from Amazon so that I can watch it over and over again.  Trust me on this:  if you take a chance on this film (it is available on Amazon Prime), you will not regret it.

This movie was a very pleasant surprise. I was expecting a mediocre if not bad movie. Everything worked for this movie. It was funny, dramatic, real/emotional, and scenic. The acting was great! It kept me on the edge of my seat not knowing what was going to happen next, and wanting more. This is kind of unusual for a romantic comedy. The writing was superb and the music was perfect and came in the right places.  I would like to have this in my movie library.  Great job to Sam Jaeger for writing and directing it!
Nice and cozy movie.  Great for romantics.  I really enjoyed it.
Totally worth watching. Nice pace and solid dialouge and an adventure.
